    "explanation": "Girsanov's theorem is providing a way to change the drift of a Wiener process by defining a new probability measure via a Radon-Nikodym derivative. More precisely, let (Q,F:,P), for 0 < t < T, be a filtered probability space, and let $W_t$ be a Wiener process in the probability measure P. Let h; be a progressively measurable stochas- tic process such that the stochastic exponential t re Ex(h) = exp (/ hsdW, - sf neds is a martingale in the probability measure P. Define a new probability measure P over Q given by the Radon- Nikodym derivative as follows: dP r gat —= W- = : 3.1 qP = &%xP (/ hidW; 5 i hi at) (3.168) Then, $W_t$ is a Wienerprocess with drift h under thenew probability measure P. Equivalently, if we define $W_t$ by Wi = Wi - ht, then $W_t$ is a Wiener process in the P- measure. More generally, if X; is the diffusion process satisfying the SDE dX, = a( Xe, t)dW; + b(Xt, t)dt under the probability measure P, then under the probabil- ity measure P defined in (3.168), X; satisfies the following SDE “cX, oS a(Xz, t)dW: + b(Xe, t)dt = a(Xz,t) (aw, - hedt) + b(Xz, t)dt = a(Xz,t)dW + (b(Xz,t)+ hea(Xt,t)) dt. In other words, in the P-measure, X; has drift part b and diffusion part a; whereas in the P-measure, the diffusion part stays the same while the drift part becomes b+ ha.",
