    "explanation": "It is clear that one weighing does not suffice. We show that the heavy balls can be identified in only two weighings. Label the red balls Ri and Ro, the green balls Gi and G2, and the yellow balls Y; and Y2. Our first weighing is \\{Ri, Gi\\} vs. \\{Ro, Yi\\}. If the scale is in balance, then either G1 or Y; is heavy, but not both. Our second weighing is \\{Gi\\} vs. \\{Yi\\}. If G, is heavier, then the set of heavy balls is \\{R2, Gi, Y2\\}. If Y; is heavier, then the set of heavy balls is \\{Ri, G2, Yi\\}. If \\{Ri,Gi\\} is heavy, then either G: is heavy or Yi is light. Our second weighing is \\{G1, Yi\\} vs. \\{G2, Y2\\}. If the scale is in balance, then G; is heavy; hence, the set of heavy balls is \\{Ri,G1, Yo\\}. If \\{Gi, Yi\\} is heavier, then G; and Y; are both heavy. The set of heavy balls is \\{Ri,Gi,¥i\\}. If \\{G2, Yo\\} is heavier, then Gz and Y2 are both heavy. The set of heavy balls is \\{R1, G2, Yo\\}. If \\{R2, Yi\\} is heavy, then either Yi is heavy or G is light. Our second weighing is \\{G1, Yi\\} vs. \\{G2, Yo\\}. If the scale is in balance, then Yi is heavy; hence, the set of heavy balls is \\{R2,G2, Yi\\}. If \\{Gi, Yi\\} is heavy, then G; and Y; are both heavy. The set of heavy balls is \\{R2,Gi,¥i\\}. If \\{G2, Yo\\} is heavier, then Gz and Y2 are both heavy. The set of heavy balls is \\{R2,G2,Y2\\}. O",
